data.content:
Here's what changes for each item in .NET 10:

---

### 1. `WebHostBuilder` → `WebApplicationBuilder`
The legacy `WebHost.CreateDefaultBuilder()` hosting model is **removed**. Migrate to the minimal hosting model:
```csharp
// Before (.NET 9)
var host = WebHost.CreateDefaultBuilder(args)
    .UseStartup<Startup>()
    .Build();

// After (.NET 10)
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
// Move Startup.ConfigureServices logic here
var app = builder.Build();
// Move Startup.Configure logic here
app.Run();
```

---

### 2. `.WithOpenApi()` removed
The per-endpoint `WithOpenApi()` extension is **removed**. Use the built-in OpenAPI document generation with transformers:
```csharp
// Before
app.MapGet("/items", () => ...).WithOpenApi();

// After — register at the service level
builder.Services.AddOpenApi(options =>
{
    options.AddOperationTransformer((operation, context, ct) =>
    {
        // per-operation customization here
        return Task.CompletedTask;
    });
});
app.MapOpenApi();
```

---

### 3. `<IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers>` removed
This MSBuild property (which pulled in `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Api.Analyzers`) is **removed**. The equivalent analysis is now built into the framework's OpenAPI analyzers automatically when you reference `Microsoft.AspNetCore.OpenApi`. Remove the property from your `.csproj`:
```xml
<!-- Delete this line -->
<IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers>true</IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers>
```

---

### 4. `Microsoft.Extensions.ApiDescription.Client` (NSwag)
This package for build-time client generation still works but now targets the **built-in OpenAPI document** (`app.MapOpenApi()`) rather than Swashbuckle-generated docs. Ensure your `<OpenApiReference>` entries point to the new endpoint (default `/openapi/v1.json`) and update the package to the .NET 10-compatible version. If you used NSwag with Swashbuckle middleware, remove `Swashbuckle.AspNetCore` and rely on `MapOpenApi()` as the document source.

---

### 5. `IActionContextAccessor` as singleton
Singleton registration now **throws** at startup due to stricter scope-validation. `IActionContextAccessor` captures scoped `ActionContext` data, so it must be scoped:
```csharp
// Before
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IActionContextAccessor, ActionContextAccessor>();

// After
builder.Services.AddHttpContextAccessor();                         // if you need HttpContext
builder.Services.AddScoped<IActionContextAccessor, ActionContextAccessor>(); // if you need ActionContext
```

---

### 6. `IPNetwork` type replaced
`Microsoft.AspNetCore.HttpOverrides.IPNetwork` is **removed**. Use the BCL type `System.Net.IPNetwork` (available since .NET 8):
```csharp
// Before
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.HttpOverrides;
options.KnownNetworks.Add(new IPNetwork(IPAddress.Parse("10.0.0.0"), 8));

// After
using System.Net;
options.KnownNetworks.Add(new IPNetwork(IPAddress.Parse("10.0.0.0"), 8));
```
The constructor signature changes — `System.Net.IPNetwork` uses `new IPNetwork(IPAddress prefix, int prefixLength)` with the same parameter order, but it's a different type. Update your `using` directives.

---

### 7. `AddRazorRuntimeCompilation()` removed
Runtime compilation of Razor views/pages is **removed** in .NET 10. The `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Razor.RuntimeCompilation` package no longer ships. Use **Hot Reload** instead:
```bash
dotnet watch
```
Remove the package reference and the `AddRazorRuntimeCompilation()` call:
```xml
<!-- Delete -->
<PackageReference Include="Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Razor.RuntimeCompilation" ... />
```

---

### 8. 401 → login redirect on API endpoints
.NET 10 changes the default cookie authentication behavior. APIs now return **401/403 status codes** instead of redirecting to the login page when the request has an `Accept: application/json` header or lacks `text/html`. If you had a manual workaround, you can simplify:
```csharp
// Before — manual workaround
services.ConfigureApplicationCookie(options =>
{
    options.Events.OnRedirectToLogin = ctx =>
    {
        ctx.Response.StatusCode = 401;
        return Task.CompletedTask;
    };
});

// After — automatic for API requests, but you can still override:
services.ConfigureApplicationCookie(options =>
{
    // Default behavior now returns 401 for non-browser requests
    // Only customize if you need different logic
});
```

---

### Summary checklist

| Item | Action |
|---|---|
| `WebHostBuilder` | Rewrite to `WebApplication.CreateBuilder()` |
| `.WithOpenApi()` | Remove; use `AddOpenApi()` + transformers |
| `IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers` | Delete from `.csproj` |
| `ApiDescription.Client` | Update package; point to `/openapi/v1.json` |
| `IActionContextAccessor` | Change to `AddScoped` |
| `IPNetwork` | Switch `using` to `System.Net` |
| `AddRazorRuntimeCompilation()` | Remove; use `dotnet watch` |
| 401 redirect | Remove manual workaround; now automatic |
